vine 1.2.0
prefix: lm
title: Modal Qwen trial in VS Code Chat
---
[lm] Decide whether Modal-hosted Qwen merits continuation (planning)
The destination is an owner decision grounded in direct use, not a production platform.
Complete when the owner has enough observed use to decide whether this stops here or informs later Coven work.
-> lm/trial
> Scope ends at an owner usage decision in VS Code; generic agent infrastructure, evaluation platforms, and Coven integration are later owner decisions.
> Human-owned specification remains design authority. This VINE owns execution order, open gaps, and dated evidence.
@guidance text/markdown human-owned-spec/initial-spec.md
---
[lm/trial] Run the owner usage trial (notstarted)
Use the configured model in ordinary VS Code work and retain observations under the owner-defined trial contract.
Accept: the planned usage sample is complete and its observations are available for the owner decision.
-> lm/design/trial
-> lm/requires/chat
-> lm/requires/operable
-> lm/requires/tools
---
[lm/design/trial] Design with user: usage trial (planning)
Define the tasks, duration, observations, comparison baseline, and stopping condition that make the usage trial informative.
Accept: the owner says the trial contract is sufficient to answer the destination question.
---
[lm/requires/chat] Requires: selectable streamed chat (notstarted)
What would satisfy the trial: the selected Qwen model appears in VS Code's model picker and completes an ordinary streamed chat response.
This node owns the requirement only; implementation choices live below verification.
-> lm/verify/chat
---
[lm/requires/tools] Requires: MCP tool round-trip (notstarted)
What would satisfy the trial: in agent mode, Qwen requests an existing MCP tool, VS Code invokes it, and Qwen uses the returned result.
This node owns the requirement only; implementation choices live below verification.
-> lm/verify/tools
> VS Code owns MCP discovery and tool invocation. The provider owns only the selected model API's tool-call and tool-result protocol.
---
[lm/requires/operable] Requires: bounded and controlled Modal trial (notstarted)
What would satisfy the trial: deployment is repeatable, ingress is controlled, spend can be stopped, and measured limits are recorded without overstatement.
This node owns the requirement only; implementation choices live below verification.
-> lm/verify/operable
---
[lm/verify/chat] Verify selectable streamed chat (notstarted)
Exercise the selected Custom Endpoint API from VS Code with a normal prompt.
Accept: model selection succeeds and the response streams to completion without protocol repair outside the selected stack.
-> lm/implement/vscode
---
[lm/verify/tools] Verify MCP tool round-trip (notstarted)
Exercise agent mode with a prompt that requires Scout's docs_search tool.
Accept: the endpoint emits a valid streamed tool call, VS Code invokes docs_search, the endpoint accepts the tool result, and the final answer uses it.
-> lm/implement/vscode
---
[lm/verify/operable] Verify trial operations and boundary (notstarted)
Exercise deploy, authenticated and rejected requests, warm invocation, and deliberate shutdown.
Accept: commands and observations reproduce the boundary, measured context/concurrency, startup behavior, and spend controls.
-> lm/implement/edge
-> lm/implement/operations
---
[lm/implement/vscode] Implement VS Code provider configuration (notstarted)
Configure the selected Custom Endpoint API, URL, credential carriage, model id, tool capability, streaming, and measured token limits.
Accept: configuration contains no guessed limits or credentials in tracked repository files.
-> lm/implement/edge
-> lm/implement/operations
---
[lm/implement/edge] Implement controlled ingress (notstarted)
Implement the owner-selected edge control so only intended API routes are reachable and authenticated from VS Code.
Accept: accepted and rejected request probes demonstrate the selected boundary; no unselected engine control or inference route is Internet-reachable.
-> lm/design/auth
-> lm/implement/cornerstone
---
[lm/implement/operations] Implement repeatable trial operations (notstarted)
Implement model/cache persistence, deploy, warm-state controls, observability needed by acceptance, and explicit shutdown.
Accept: another run can reproduce deployment and teardown from repository commands without unstated state.
-> lm/design/runtime
-> lm/implement/cornerstone
---
[lm/implement/cornerstone] Lay the cornerstone (notstarted)
Instantiate only the selected bakeoff winner: pinned engine and model artifact, chosen API surface, chosen Modal GPU cell, and one direct streaming smoke request.
This is the first product implementation; bakeoff probes remain experimental and are not promoted wholesale.
Accept: the selected checkpoint loads and one direct request streams on the chosen Modal cell.
-> lm/design/stack
> No product cornerstone is laid until the bakeoff observations are reviewed and the owner selects one stack.
---
[lm/design/auth] Design with user: public-edge authentication (planning)
Choose credential storage, VS Code carriage, route allowlisting, and the component that authenticates before exposing the endpoint.
The design must account for the selected engine's complete route surface and Modal's available edge controls.
Accept: the owner selects one testable boundary with no implicit public routes.
-> lm/research/auth
---
[lm/research/auth] Resolve authentication capabilities (notstarted)
Measure VS Code Custom Endpoint credential/header behavior and enumerate Modal or reverse-proxy shapes that can expose only the selected API routes.
Known 2026-07-17: Modal proxy auth uses Modal-Key plus Modal-Secret; vLLM --api-key protects selected API prefixes but not its whole HTTP surface. These are candidate observations, not a selected design.
Report: exact configuration surfaces, secret locations, reachable routes, and request probes; no preferred design verdict.
-> lm/research/engines
-> lm/research/vscode-contract
@guidance text/html https://modal.com/docs/guide/webhook-proxy-auth
@guidance text/html https://modal.com/docs/sdk/py/latest/modal.web_server
---
[lm/design/runtime] Design with user: runtime and cost policy (planning)
Choose GPU count, served context, concurrency, warm-state policy, cache persistence, and spend controls from measured bakeoff and Modal data.
Accept: every promised limit is measured and every always-on cost has an explicit owner control.
-> lm/bakeoff/report
-> lm/research/modal-runtime
---
[lm/research/modal-runtime] Resolve Modal runtime controls (notstarted)
Collect current first-party behavior and pricing for candidate GPUs, Volumes, web serving, concurrency, autoscaling, deployment, and shutdown.
Known 2026-07-17: Modal lists gpu=RTX-PRO-6000; NVIDIA specifies 96 GB GDDR7; Modal listed $0.000842/s. Values must be refreshed when the cell is admitted.
Report: dated handles and numeric inputs needed by runtime design; no preferred policy verdict.
@guidance text/html https://modal.com/docs/guide/gpu
@guidance text/html https://modal.com/pricing
@guidance text/html https://modal.com/docs/guide/volumes
@guidance text/html https://modal.com/docs/guide/scale
@guidance text/html https://modal.com/docs/guide/secrets
@guidance text/html https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/data-center/rtx-pro-6000-blackwell-server-edition/
