[lm/design/stack] Design with user: select the trial stack (planning)
Review bakeoff data and select one exact engine revision, model artifact revision, API type, tool parser path, GPU cell, and initial context target.
Accept: the owner selects one stack; unselected implementations do not enter product code.
-> lm/bakeoff/report
---
[lm/bakeoff/report] Publish bakeoff observations (notstarted)
Publish raw and summarized observations for every admitted cell under the ruled protocol.
Report data: load success, versions, conditions, VRAM, context/concurrency, TTFT, prefill/decode rates, tool-call traces, startup time, and estimated Modal cost.
Accept: failed and successful cells are both represented and rerun commands are attached.
-> lm/bakeoff/run
---
[lm/bakeoff/run] Run the engine and deployment bakeoff (notstarted)
Run every admitted cell with the same ruled workload and repetition scheme.
Accept: each result is attributable to exact engine, artifact, GPU, API, and configuration revisions.
-> lm/implement/bakeoff
---
[lm/implement/bakeoff] Implement the bakeoff harness (notstarted)
Build disposable probes and capture for model load, memory, protocol streaming, MCP tool round-trip, latency, throughput, startup, and teardown.
Keep experimental engine integrations isolated from product implementation.
Accept: one command per admitted cell produces the ruled observation schema and preserves raw output.
-> lm/design/bakeoff
---
[lm/design/bakeoff] Design with user: bakeoff contract (planning)
Define admitted candidates, workloads, measures, repetitions, failure recording, resource budget, and stopping condition.
The owner leads the evaluation shape; the agent drafts the executable contract.
Accept: the owner confirms the contract can distinguish a stack suitable for the destination.
-> lm/design/api-surface
-> lm/design/model-cells
-> lm/research/engines
> No serving engine has prior status. Admit vLLM, SGLang, TensorRT-LLM, or another challenger only when the research gates show the exact model and required VS Code surface are supportable.
---
[lm/design/model-cells] Design with user: model and compute cells (planning)
Choose which exact BF16, official FP8, and candidate 4-bit revisions and which one- or multi-GPU Modal cells enter the bakeoff.
Accept: each admitted cell has a falsifiable load hypothesis, bounded cost, and pinned artifact handle.
-> lm/research/model-footprint
> The base model identity is fixed by the owner as Qwen/Qwen3-Next-80B-A3B-Instruct. Quantized artifact revisions, GPU count, and GPU type remain bakeoff cells.
---
[lm/research/model-footprint] Resolve model footprint and artifact candidates (notstarted)
Measure repository bytes and dtype counts, calculate memory floors, resolve exact revisions, and identify first-party versus community quantizations.
Known 2026-07-17: official FP8 revision c5f5f263bdd5cc134092897864e8905d8fe7b928 has 82,051,854,384 safetensor bytes (76.417 GiB): 80,636,542,976 FP8, 688,319,744 BF16, and 4,921,664 F32 parameters. This is a storage floor, not measured runtime VRAM. Qwen publishes BF16 and FP8; a one-GPU 4-bit artifact is unresolved.
Report: checkpoint bytes, runtime-memory unknowns, documented engine/GPU requirements, and candidate handles; do not infer fit from active parameter count.
@guidance text/html https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-Next-80B-A3B-Instruct
@guidance text/html https://huggingface.co/Qwen/Qwen3-Next-80B-A3B-Instruct-FP8
---
[lm/design/api-surface] Design with user: VS Code API surface (planning)
Choose which VS Code Custom Endpoint API types enter the bakeoff: Chat Completions, Responses, and/or Messages.
Accept: each admitted surface has an end-to-end streaming and tool-result round-trip witness.
-> lm/research/vscode-contract
---
[lm/research/vscode-contract] Resolve VS Code provider contract (notstarted)
Extract the current Custom Endpoint request, streaming, tool-calling, credential, token-limit, and agent-mode requirements from pinned first-party docs and focused probes.
Known 2026-07-17: VS Code Custom Endpoint offers Chat Completions, Responses, and Messages API types; agent mode requires tool calling; VS Code discovers and invokes MCP tools.
Report: exact fields and observed wire behavior for each candidate API type.
@guidance text/html https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/agent-customization/language-models
@guidance text/html https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/agent-customization/mcp-servers
---
[lm/research/engines] Resolve admissible serving engines (notstarted)
Build a first-party support matrix for the exact Qwen3-Next architecture and artifact candidates across vLLM, SGLang, TensorRT-LLM, and any challenger that passes all gates.
Known 2026-07-17: vLLM's Qwen3-Next recipe uses TP4, prefix caching, and Hermes tool parsing; Qwen's official SGLang command also uses TP4. Neither is a selection or proof that one 96 GB GPU cannot work.
Gates: load support, selected quantization/GPU support, VS Code-compatible API, streamed automatic tool calls, tool-result continuation, and measurable runtime statistics.
Report exclusions with evidence; do not carry unsupported engines into the bakeoff.
@guidance text/html https://docs.vllm.ai/projects/recipes/en/latest/Qwen/Qwen3-Next.html
@guidance text/html https://docs.vllm.ai/en/stable/serving/online_serving/
@guidance text/html https://docs.vllm.ai/en/stable/features/tool_calling/
@guidance text/html https://docs.vllm.ai/en/stable/usage/security/#api-key-authentication-limitations
@guidance text/html https://docs.vllm.ai/en/stable/features/automatic_prefix_caching/
